Ivy Tech Madison Community Resource of the Day...

In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, Ivy Tech Madison strives to provide our students access to resources during this difficult time. We will be sharing local and national resources that we have been made aware of in hopes it can assist our students...

Ivy Tech Madison in partnership with WorkOne Southeast, River Valley Resources, Inc. and the Madison Area Chamber of Commerce will be hosting six, small virtual job fairs with 3-4 employers each week. Ivy Tech Community College has announced it is offering free classes and trainings for 10,000 participants. The College is elevating its commitment to Hoosiers impacted by COVID-19 experiencing unemployment, reduced hours, and/or furloughs across the state. Participants may take more than one class or training in a range of relevant high-demand areas.

Hoosiers can get detailed information about the classes and trainings, and register for free, by visiting
https://www.ivytech.edu/10kclasses

shared_text:
Indiana Department of Workforce Development
April 24 at 2:16 PM ·

Applying for PUA Benefits – What to Expect

The CARES Act Pandemic Unemployment Assistance (PUA) program provides assistance for those previously not covered by traditional unemployment insurance - the self-employed, contractors, gig economy workers and others. DWD has completed construction of the new system, and the PUA application is now available to those that have applied for and been denied regular UI. You will find it on your Claimant Home page under TO DO. You must apply for and be denied regular UI before you will have the PUA application link. Before applying, it is recommended that you review the Frequently Asked Questions on www.Unemployment.IN.gov.

Applying for PUA Benefits – What to Expect

The CARES Act Pandemic Unemployment Assistance (PUA) program provides assistance for those previously not covered by traditional unemployment insurance - the self-employed, contractors, gig economy workers and others. DWD has completed construction of the new system, and the PUA application is now available to those that have applied for and been denied regular UI. You will find it on your Claimant Home page under TO DO. You must apply for and be denied regular UI before you will have the PUA application link. Before applying, it is recommended that you review the Frequently Asked Questions on www.Unemployment.IN.gov.

April 3 at 10:06 AM ·

Want to improve your internet? Write a letter!
REMC and SEI Communications are applying for a Next Level grant to provide broadband service to REMC customers. They need letters of support, and Switzerland County can make a good case for this! Tell the state about the difficulties you have without broadband and/or what you could accomplish with Broadband*. Send your letters to me at sbrichto@gmail.com. Don't forget your name and address. Letters go out Tuesday morning. Let's convince them WE NEED BROADBAND!!
*(The official FCC broadband definition is a minimum of 25 Mbps download and 3 Mbps upload.)
P.S.- Students, there's a contest for the best 3 letters, we only have 2....

post_text: Here are excerpts from a success story from my Versailles class. A mere month after assuming responsibility for the Vevay class I can see we're getting close to having successful graduates at this location, too.
shared_text:
Richard Ries
January 29, 2018 at 7:31 PM ·

The State is asking us for success stories from our classrooms and I thought my past student Hannah Silverthorn would be a good example. I asked her to relate her experiences. What she wrote is beautifully compelling. I’ll provide more later, but here are a couple of quotes. “I realized I had no education and would be stuck in a toxic work environment.” “It’s hard when you realize as a young adult that life’s just started and you’re already failing.” “When you first meet Rich he is kind of intimidating but I wouldn’t have chosen anyone else to be my instructor.” “My career is set and I’m ready to take sail.” This is exactly why I get such joy from my job. (Hannah in uniform; she's a security guard.)

post_text:
Greetings Switzerland County! I hope everyone is enjoying the Holiday Season. Today was my last day as an Adult Education Instructor in Switzerland County. I have accepted a position at Ivy Tech in Madison as the Assistant Director of Student Support and Development. It is with a heavy heart that I leave Switzerland County. The students and community of Switzerland County have touched my heart and it has been my pleasure to serve this county; HOWEVER-- I leave you in wonderful hands. Please join me in welcoming our new Adult Ed Instructor, Rich Ries. I will let him tell you more about himself, but I wanted to give him his official welcome! Rich is an amazing educator and I know Switzerland County will gain so much by having him onboard! Please join me in welcoming Rich! Rich will continue with the regular hours we have established for the next two weeks before making any adjustments. Tentatively, he plans to continue Wednesdays and Fridays with a possible open lab Thursday evenings.

Again, thank you for all who have supported this program and me! Stay in touch!

-Nina
